4. COMBAT PHILOSOPHY

Combat in Possibly a Hero is intentional. Nothing procs automatically. Nothing
kills enemies the player wasn't involved in killing.

Powers are tools. Players aim them, time them, position them, and combine them
through active decision. A Brawler who pulls a cluster together with Magnetism
and then drops a Shockwave into the center of the pile is playing differently
from a Brawler throwing Shockwaves at whatever is closest. Both land hits.
Only one reflects mastery.

A skilled player with a mediocre power selection outperforms an unskilled
player with a great one. This is a design commitment, not an aspiration.
Mastery is real in Possibly a Hero and it is expressible. The game does not
paper over player error with automatic output.

Power selection at milestone (level up):

At each milestone, the player chooses between three genuinely viable options:
- A class primary upgrade — deepens core class identity and sharpens what
  the class already does
- A hero power — adds a new tool to the run, broadens capability, introduces
  combo potential
- A support option — modifies existing powers, shifts how the build interacts
  with enemies and terrain

No option is obviously correct. The selection is not a trap with two wrong
answers. Build identity emerges from the accumulated weight of these choices
across the full run — not from a preset configuration the player carried in.
A run that opened with Tempest and layered Blast Radius on top plays
differently from a run that opened with Reflexes and built toward Velocity
Slam. Neither is the prescribed path. Both are valid.

Combat feel reference: Hades
Structural loop reference: Vampire Survivors
These references describe different dimensions of the same game.

