5. THE THREE MISSION TYPES

Post-tutorial, all three mission types spawn in every run — simultaneously,
at the Act Two reveal. They are not separate modes. They are live locations
within a single run environment. The player is always in the same run, on
the same map, with all three available from the moment they spawn.

Mission spawn locations are randomized each run. No mission type has a
fixed geographic position. Every spawn lands outside the hero's proximity
trigger radius at the moment of reveal.

BOSS FIGHT
Type: Action combat encounter
Objective: Defeat the encounter boss
City output: Generates resources for city construction

A direct confrontation. The player's power combination is tested against a
specific challenge that requires positioning and timing to resolve cleanly.
Boss Fight rewards are load-bearing for city development — players who skip
boss encounters are players whose city stops growing.

PASSIVE ESCORT DEFENSE
Type: Moving objective protection
Objective: Keep a moving objective alive from point A to point B
City output: Sustains city morale

The hero is not the only thing moving. Enemies read the objective as the
priority, not the player. The player has to stay between the threat and the
thing they're protecting. Positioning and camera awareness matter more here
than in any other mission type. A build optimized for stationary output will
feel the gap in an escort run. The objective does not wait for the player to
solve problems from a distance.

HORDE SURVIVAL
Type: Position hold
Objective: Survive in a defined zone for a set duration while enemy density
escalates
City output: Generates intel

The enemies come to the player. The build gets stress-tested at volume. How
a power combination performs under sustained pressure in a fixed location is
a fundamentally different question from how it performs in an open engagement.
The run's loadout choices either hold or they don't.

Intel and the area boss:
Intel is not optional. Horde Survival is the only mission type that generates
it. Accumulated intel identifies the area's super villain. Sufficient intel
triggers the area boss encounter. The area boss gates progression to the next
stage. All three mission types become structurally necessary — the player
cannot progress past an area without running the horde survival loop enough
times to build the intel picture.

