6. MINOR OBJECTIVES

Minor objectives exist between and alongside formal missions throughout every
run. Muggings. Citizens in danger. Environmental incidents the hero happens to
be close enough to see. These are opportunities, not assignments. No system
routes the player toward them. No timer forces a response. They appear because
the city is a place, and things happen in places.

Minor objectives are what the Hades camera distance makes possible. At this
angle, a person in trouble three blocks from the horde zone is visible. The
player can see the mugging. They can choose to stop.

Minor objectives feed:
- XP — direct boost to run progression. Minor objective XP feeds the same
  milestone-based power selection system as combat XP. More minor objectives
  completed means more power selection opportunities within a run. A player
  who stays engaged with the city between missions levels up faster and builds
  more.
- Hero Points — guaranteed drop from every minor objective completed, at 100%
  rate. Rewards meaningfully more than a single mob drop. Full carry between
  runs — what the player earns is theirs permanently, regardless of run
  outcome.
- City morale (Citizens channel) — citizens saw what the hero did, or didn't
  do, on their block
- Recognition (Superhero Community channel) — the community tracks patterns
  across the run record
- Clickbait (Rex Flynn / Exposed channel) — Rex was almost certainly filming
  something nearby for unrelated reasons

Minor objectives do not generate intel. Intel is the exclusive output of Horde
Survival. The horde survival mission cannot be bypassed through incidental
heroism, no matter how many minor objectives the player engages.

The XP connection makes minor objectives a genuine strategic layer, not just
atmosphere. A player who wants more power selection opportunities in a run has
a reason to pay attention to the city between missions — not because the game
told them to, but because the city keeps presenting situations and the
situations keep being worth something.

Minor objectives are the single most natural source of early name emergence.
Citizens name heroes they watch doing things before any formal mission is
completed. The pattern of what the player does between objectives becomes part
of the record before the player realizes they're writing one.

