7. RUN TIME STRUCTURE — THREE ACTS

A run is twenty minutes. Not a target, not a rhythm — a wall. The run ends
at the wall, on player-chosen extraction, or when the hero is taken out of
the fight, whichever comes first. Every run has the same shape. The map,
the mission spawns, and the build are different every time. The shape is
not.

The three acts are information states, not rule states. Nothing the player
can do in one act is forbidden in another. What changes is what the player
knows and what exists on the map. Build development is continuous for the
entire run — milestone level-ups fire whenever XP earns them, from the
first minute to the last. There is no build phase. There is no point at
which loadout development stops.

ACT ONE — PREP PERIOD (0:00 – 5:00)

The three missions have not spawned. They are not hidden somewhere on the
map waiting to be found — they do not exist yet. Nothing the player does
during the prep period can trigger a mission, and nothing can blindside
them.

The player moves through the city freely, leveling up through milestone-
based power selections. Minor objectives are live. Enemies are live. The
build is forming. The city is already reacting to the fact that someone is
out there. The prep period has tension — it comes from the streets, not
from a mission waiting to ambush a two-power hero around the wrong corner.

ACT TWO — OPEN WINDOW (5:00 – 15:00)

At the five-minute mark, all three missions spawn and reveal
simultaneously. Each spawns outside the hero's current proximity trigger
radius — guaranteed safe distance at the moment of reveal. From that
moment, every mission is live and triggerable by player movement. A
mission trigger is always the result of the player's choice to approach.
Never an accident. Never an ambush.

Full information. Full agency. And a genuine decision with teeth: every
minute spent building is a minute not spent executing. The player who
commits at minute seven with a lean build is buying mission attempts with
power they didn't take. The player who builds until the gate is buying
power with attempts they may not get. The longer you wait, the stronger
you get — and the less wall time remains to do anything with it. The Open
Window is where that trade is made, remade, and lived with.

THE GATE — FORCED COMMITMENT (15:00)

At the fifteen-minute mark, the gate. It is hard. The player must have
committed to at least one mission by the gate or the run fails. This is
not a penalty for slow play. It is the game asking the question the entire
run was building toward: you've been building — now what are you going to
do with it? Not committing is not a neutral choice in a game about
becoming a hero. It is a refusal to be the thing the game is about. The
gate is not the punishment. The gate is the point.

The gate is a minimum threshold, not a starting gun. Most runs commit long
before it. The gate exists for the run where the player builds and builds
and never answers the question.

ACT THREE — EXECUTION (15:00 – 20:00)

Committed play until the wall. No mission carries its own timer — the wall
is the only clock, and it was always the only clock. The player sequences
whatever missions remain against whatever time remains, with whatever
they've built. Building between missions is sanctioned play. Pivoting from
a completed mission back into development before attempting the next is
sanctioned play. The wall makes every strategy honest.

A prepared player resolves a single mission in roughly five minutes — the
twenty-minute figure is the natural rhythm of a well-executed minimum run.
The exceptional run and the perfect run are not longer runs. They are
better ones.

