8. RUN RESOLUTION

A run ends at the wall, on extraction, or when the hero is taken out of
the fight. Resolution grades what is true at that moment.

Completion tiers:
- MINIMUM SUCCESS — one mission complete
- EXCEPTIONAL — two missions complete
- PERFECT — three missions complete

Mission outputs are earned at mission completion, not at run end. Outputs
stack — a perfect run feeds resources, morale, and intel into the city
simultaneously. Mission priority and sequencing are the player's strategic
decision, tied to their own progression goals. A player who needs intel
opens with Horde Survival. A player who needs construction resources hunts
the Boss Fight first. The game does not rank the missions. The city does
not care about the order. It cares about what got done.

Banked missions are permanent within the run. Being taken out of the fight
after completing a mission costs the player the opportunity at a higher
tier — never the tier already earned. The citizens a hero saved do not
become unsaved because the hero got knocked out afterward. What was earned
at the moment it was earned is the player's. Extraction exists for the
player who is done — it ends the run early and grades it as it stands. It
protects nothing, because nothing needs protecting.

Hero Points accumulate from mob drops and minor objectives across the full
run — full carry, no reduction, regardless of outcome.

Failed run — zero missions complete, by gate refusal or by being taken out
of the fight before banking a mission: atmospheric consequence only. No
progress is reversed. No construction is undone. No city building
disappears. Hero Points earned during the run carry forward in full. The
city absorbs the loss without surrendering it. The player returns to a
city that knows things went badly, not a city that was set back.

Run patterns accumulate. A streak of bad runs darkens the city over a
short window — citizens pull indoors, visual tone shifts, Rex Flynn has
opinions he broadcasts at volume. None of it is permanent. The city
recovers. The hero goes again. The story keeps writing itself, one run at
a time, whether the last run was the best one or the worst one in the
record.

